PI Data Security Strategies
1. Minimize Collection
•	Collect only the PI data strictly needed for the business purpose.
•	Use data classification to identify what counts as PI and avoid unnecessary storage.
2. Protect Data in Transit
•	Use TLS/SSL for all network communication.
•	Enforce HTTPS everywhere and disable insecure protocols.
3. Protect Data at Rest
•	Encrypt PI using strong algorithms (AES-256).
•	Use managed key stores or hardware security modules (HSMs) for key management.
4. Access Control
•	Apply least privilege access for users, services, and applications.
•	Use strong authentication (MFA) and role-based access control (RBAC).
5. Data Masking and Tokenization
•	Mask or redact PI in logs, UIs, and reports.
•	Tokenize sensitive values so raw PI is not stored in primary systems.
6. Auditing and Monitoring
•	Log access to PI and monitor for suspicious activity.
•	Keep audit trails for changes, access, and data exports.
7. Data Retention and Disposal
•	Define clear retention policies for PI.
•	Securely delete or anonymize PI when no longer needed.
8. Segmentation and Isolation
•	Segment networks and systems that handle PI.
•	Isolate PI processing from lower-security environments.
9. Secure Development Practices
•	Use secure coding standards to prevent injection, XSS, CSRF, and other vulnerabilities.
•	Validate and sanitize all input that may include PI.
10. Compliance and Policy
•	Align with relevant regulations and standards (GDPR, CCPA, PCI DSS, ISO 27001).
•	Document policies, train staff, and review them regularly.
